@adoroszlai, I didn't touch `ambari-serviceadvisor` for the very reason you mentioned:

> which does not inherit from the same parent, and still has 1.0.0.0-SNAPSHOT?

Since it doesn't inherit from the parent, it can have its own release cycle independent from Ambari. However, if we feel that this should also match the rest of the project (since it is an integral part of the product), then we can update it as well.

Thoughts?

@jonathan-hurley note (i guess you know that, but worth to mention here) if that revision support is only available from maven 3.5.0, we should update cwiki with that we require at least maven 3.5.x + CI/Releng will need to use that version. it's good maven have something like that, probably we will use that in ambari-infra and ambari-logsearch as well. also note that if only the version is defined in one place, with a build script (like with Makefile), the snapshot version can be calculated as well (from the last release: release-2.7.1, that can be 2.8.0.0-SNAPSHOT - of course the default in pom.xml would be 3.0.0.0-SNAPSHOT as you provided in the patch) e.g.: i did that in one of my project: https://github.com/oleewere/ambarictl/blob/master/Makefile#L22 , it's not a maven project, but good example for the version calculation).

@oleewere yes, once this commit passes and gets pushed, we'll need to update the wiki to include the changes to the minimum maven version and the release process.

By parameterizing the version in this way, it does allow us to quickly swap it out like so:
```
mvn -Drevision=2.8.0.0-SNAPSHOT clean package
```
Is that what you were saying?

versioning blueprint (ambari version) is not required anymore? cc @rnettleton (anyway i think 99% of the cases that is fine)

Hi @oleewere , I don't think we ever supported including the Ambari Server version in an exported Blueprint in any previous Ambari Server release.  

We have discussed it as a helper in order to make moving older Blueprints to newer Ambari versions a little simpler, but we don't have any plans to add this at this point. 

I'll give some thought to creating a JIRA for this, since it may be good to add this information in the exported Blueprint in Ambari 2.8.  

Thanks.

@sjanardhanhw I can't remember exactly. But generally speaking, just decreasing the left margin might not address the issue for all possible cases (since non-monotype font is used for cluster name, and different char combination would have different widths). Also, negative margin might potentially cause intersection with breadcrumbs block.
Actually it would be better to look at arrangement of children of `<div class="container main-container">`, since the issue is caused by insufficient width for cluster name element.

My concern with changing this command is that if an environment relies on `curl` reading `http_proxy`, then this change would break them. Instead, we should change Ambari to be able to configure this on a per-environment basis.

I'm closing this review as it's a year old without being merged. It can be re-opened with new code if necessary.
